The problem with bentonite is that it's an expansive clay--as it absorbs water it gets bigger. It's used in soil sampling to backfill holes in the soil (unless you're a geologist, then it's "holes in the sediment") because of this property--pour enough in and it fills in the voids as it gets wet. A lot of it has a coating on it to prevent this from happening TOO fast. If you put too much bentonite in, you get "bentonite snot", this runny clay with the consistency of mucus flowing over the ground. Not fun to clean up.
